overview: The user initiated the conversation by requesting fixes for numerous
  issues in a pull request, emphasizing critical security flaws and broken
  Vercel deployments. The agent began by systematically identifying and
  addressing a wide range of problems. Initial lint errors were resolved by
  pushing existing local fixes. A major security vulnerability related to
  trivially forgeable admin authentication cookies was fixed by implementing
  HMAC-based session tokens using the Web Crypto API, ensuring compatibility
  with Vercel's Edge Runtime. API routes and CSV exports were secured with
  pagination and limits to prevent resource exhaustion. PDF generation logic was
  refined to correctly handle time inputs and display generic user names. A
  critical turning point was the discovery of a Next.js security vulnerability
  (CVE-2025-66478), which necessitated an upgrade to Next.js 16.1.1. This
  upgrade, however, introduced further breaking changes, requiring a migration
  of the ESLint configuration to a flat format and adjustments to the Prisma
  setup. Persistent Vercel deployment failures were traced to the Prisma client
  attempting to connect during build time without the  environment
  variable, which was resolved by implementing lazy-loading for the Prisma
  client. Finally, outdated e2e tests were updated to reflect the current
  application content. Through these iterative fixes and adaptations to breaking
  changes, all GitHub Actions and Vercel deployments were successfully brought
  to a passing state.
